{{other people|Mary Eaton}} {{Infobox artist | name = Mary Emily Eaton | image = <!-- just the pagename, without the File:/Image: prefix or [[brackets]] --> | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = <!-- only use if different than name --> | birth_date = {{Birth date|1873|11|27|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Coleford, Gloucestershire]], U.K. | death_date = {{Death date and age|1961|08|04|1873|11|27|df=y}} | death_place = [[Cossington, Somerset]], U.K. | nationality = British | education = | alma_mater = | known_for = Botanical art | notable_works = | style = | awards = Grenfell Medal, Royal Horticultural Society (twice) }}
'''Mary Emily Eaton''' (27 November 1873 – 4 August 1961) was an English botanical artist best known for illustrating [[Nathaniel Lord Britton|Britton]] & [[Joseph Nelson Rose|Rose]]'s ''[[The Cactaceae]]'', published between 1919 and 1923.<ref name=smithsonian/>
[[Image:The Cactaceae Vol III, plate XIX filtered.jpg|thumb|<center>Plate XIX from ''The Cactaceae''</center>]] [[Image:Ancistrocactus scheeri00.jpg|thumb|<center>''Sclerocactus scheeri''</center>]]
==Life== Mary Emily Eaton was born on 27 November 1873 in [[Coleford, Gloucestershire]]. She attended private schools in London and received formal tuition in art at the [[Somerset College of Arts and Technology|Taunton School of Art]], also attending classes at the [[Royal College of Art]] in [[South Kensington]], and the [[Chelsea Polytechnic]].<ref name=smithsonian/>
She worked for a time as a painter of [[Worcester porcelain]], before going to [[Jamaica]] in 1909 to visit her siblings.<ref name=smithsonian/><ref name=kramer1/> During her two-years stay, she began painting detailed studies of butterflies and moths.<ref name=smithsonian/>
In June 1911 Eaton left for [[New York City]], where she would remain until January 1932, employed by [[The New York Botanical Garden]].<ref name=smithsonian/><ref name=kramer1/> Among other duties, she was the principal illustrator for the Botanical Garden's journal ''[[Addisonia (journal)|Addisonia]]'', painting over three-quarters of the 800 plates. She was the principal illustrator for Britton & Rose's monumental work ''[[The Cactaceae]]'', and her illustrations also appeared in the [[National Geographic Magazine]]. Contemporary authorities rated her work very highly, one source calling her "the greatest of living wildflower painters" and another stating that one could not fully appreciate her talent from the sometimes mediocre reproductions of her work in ''Addisonia'' and other publications.<ref name=kramer1/>
She was awarded the silver-gilt Grenfell Medal of the [[Royal Horticultural Society]] twice, first in 1922 and again in 1950.<ref name=kramer1/>
In 1932, due to the [[Great Depression]], Eaton lost her position at the Botanic Garden, after which she struggled to find enough work in America.<ref name=kramer1/> In 1947, she returned to England, where she died on 4 August 1961 in [[Cossington, Somerset]]. Many of her paintings are at the [[Natural History Museum, London|British Museum of Natural History]].<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.asba-art.org/article/botanica-collected-mary-emily-eaton|title=Mary Emily Eaton and Her Cactaceae Paintings|author=Angell, Bobbi|journal=The Botanical Artist|volume=15|issue=3}}</ref> The Hunt Institute for Botanical Documentation also has a number of her works.<ref name=smithsonian/> Six hundred of her watercolours are part of the permanent collections of the [[National Geographic Society]], [[The New York Botanical Garden]] and the [[Smithsonian Institution]].
